From: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 15 May 2026 18:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] clk: qcom: gcc-ipq5332: mark snoc<->nssnoc bridge clocks critical

The two SNOC->NSSNOC bridge clocks (gcc_snoc_nssnoc_clk at 0x17084 and
gcc_snoc_nssnoc_1_clk at 0x17090) gate access from the system NoC to
the NSS sub-system NoC. They are enabled by the bootloader; nothing in
mainline currently requests them via clk_get(), so clk_disable_unused
turns them off during late init. Once disabled, any in-flight access
to the NSS register window from the wrong side of the fabric raises a
NoC error and the SoC resets ~20ms later.

Observed during boot on GL.iNet GL-BE9300 (Flint 3, IPQ5332) once the
NSSCC driver started registering, even before any PPE/EDMA/uniphy
consumer was wired up: kernel reached "clk: Disabling unused clocks",
brought PCIe Gen3 up, and a NoC-Error reset followed shortly after AER
init. Booting with clk_ignore_unused on the kernel command line lets
userspace come up.

Both these bridge clocks need to stay on permanently to keep the NSS
register apertures reachable from the system fabric, so mark them with
CLK_IS_CRITICAL.

Signed-off-by: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
---
--- a/drivers/clk/qcom/gcc-ipq5332.c
+++ b/drivers/clk/qcom/gcc-ipq5332.c
@@ -2587,7 +2587,7 @@ static struct clk_branch gcc_snoc_nssnoc_1_clk = {
 				&gcc_system_noc_bfdcd_clk_src.clkr.hw,
 			},
 			.num_parents = 1,
-			.flags = CLK_SET_RATE_PARENT,
+			.flags = CLK_SET_RATE_PARENT | CLK_IS_CRITICAL,
 			.ops = &clk_branch2_ops,
 		},
 	},
@@ -2605,7 +2605,7 @@ static struct clk_branch gcc_snoc_nssnoc_clk = {
 				&gcc_system_noc_bfdcd_clk_src.clkr.hw,
 			},
 			.num_parents = 1,
-			.flags = CLK_SET_RATE_PARENT,
+			.flags = CLK_SET_RATE_PARENT | CLK_IS_CRITICAL,
 			.ops = &clk_branch2_ops,
 		},
 	},
